properties.abstract: Montfort Bike offers a panoramic view across the Rhine Valley, the Liechtenstein Alps and Vorarlberg. The route’s name comes from the Counts of Montfort. For a long time, they were the owners of the castle and hamlet of Werdenberg, which gives the region its name.
properties.description:
From Buchs, you first go along the small river Giessen, through meadows and fields to Grabs. After Grabs, a slight climb over Studener Berg, with its scattered villages, leads to the highlands. Efforts are rewarded with a view over the Rhine and the mountains. You reach Sess via the Alpstrasse.

The descent through woods and meadows leads you to the Buchser Berg, to yet another ascent. A path through mixed woodland takes you to the Seveler Berg. Then the route descends to HüserenAcross the plateau on the Schaner mountain, Montfort Bike leads to Oberschan, which was formerly a mill village. Shortly before Oberschan, you have the opportunity to cool off in the Oberschan natural pool, which is located directly on the route.

When crossing the Schaner Riet, a stretch of marshland, you pass the Magletsch fortress. A short descent leads you to the hamlet of St. Ulrich, a well-preserved Walser settlement. Another ascent follows, until the path leads out of the forest. The route finally leads past the bird of prey park to the medieval town of Werdenberg. The wooden construction settlement demonstrates an astonishing variety of construction methods.  Well-preserved half-timbered buildings as well as chalets and log buildings line the townscape.  Located on a hill, Werdenberg Castle is worth a visit, with its castle museum and cosy bistro in the castle courtyard.
